    "lesson_content_markdown":  "# Thinking Words vs. Doing Words\n\nIn English, we have two types of words for what we do: **Doing Words** and **Thinking Words**.\n\n### 1. Doing Words (Action Verbs)\n\nDoing words describe something you can see. You can use the **-ing** form for these words when they are happening now.\n\n**Examples of Doing Words:**\n- **Eat**: I am eating my lunch now.\n- **Read**: You are reading a book.\n- **Walk**: The students are walking to class.\n\n### 2. Thinking Words (State Verbs)\n\nThinking words describe feelings, opinions, or facts. You **cannot** see these actions. We almost never use **-ing** for these words, even if they are true now.\n\n#### Categories of Thinking Words:\n\n**Mind (Thinking)**\n- **Understand**: I understand the homework. (Not: I am understanding)\n- **Believe**: I believe you.\n- **Know**: He knows my name.\n\n**Feelings**\n- **Like**: I like this school.\n- **Love**: She loves coffee.\n- **Want**: They want a break.\n\n**Having things**\n- **Have**: I have a red pen. (Not: I am having a red pen)\n- **Own**: The school owns three buses.\n- **Need**: You need a pencil.\n\n### Why does it matter?\n\nIf you use **-ing** with a thinking word, it sounds strange to native speakers. \n\n- **Correct**: I **know** the answer.\n- **Incorrect**: I am knowing the answer.\n\n---",
